# Aramaic Primacy - Fundamental Objections

[Projects Home](index.md) | [Aramaic Primacy](AramaicPrimacy.md)

---

## Key claims of Aramaic Primacists

These are some of the central claims of Aramaic Primacy that I have seen numerous proponents claim:

* The Jews of Palestine in the 1st Century AD spoke only Aramaic.  
* The Jews of the Diaspora brought Aramaic with them wherever they went and maintained a knowledge of Aramaic in spite of pressure from the languages in whatever environment in which they lived.   
* Jesus and the disciples spoke only Aramaic, and could not have written the texts of the New Testament in Greek.  
* The Peshitta is the original and authentic text of the New Testament.

Based on these claims, here are some fundamental objections that I have:

## *Section 1* : If *all* the New Testament was originally written by Jews, for a Jewish audience, and Aramaic was the only language of the Jews of First Century Palestine, and Greek was practically unknown among the Jews (even in the Diaspora)...

### Why are there numerous verses in various New Testament Books explaining Jewish terminology and culture, which should have been obvious to a Jewish audience?

Take, for example, John 1:38, as translated from Peshitta:

> "Jesus turned and saw them following and said to them, “What do you seek?” They said to him, *“Rabbi” (which means Teacher)*, “where are you staying?”

If the original audience of John's Gospel was Jews (regardless of which language they spoke, be it Aramaic, Hebrew, Greek or even pig Latin\!), why would they need the term “rabbi” \- ***ESPECIALLY THE TERM “RABBI”*** \- explained to them?

And then there is John 2:13:

> “And the ***Passover of the Jews*** was near, and Jesus went up to Jerusalem.”

Why the need for John to clarify that it was the Passover ***of the Jews***? Was there a Roman Passover, or an Egyptian Passover? Telling a Gentile audience that it was the Jewish Passover makes sense, but not a Jewish audience (explaining the Passover being a Jewish festival also occurs in John 6:4 and John 11:55). It’s like if someone were to say, “The time of the Christian Christmas was near,...” you would find it hard to believe such a text would have been written for a Christian audience.

Texts involving explanations of Jewish terms and customs include Mark 7:1-4, Mark 15:42, Luke 2:4, John 4:9, John 6:4, John 11:55, and Acts 23:7,8.

> "The Pharisees and the Scribes who had come from Jerusalem gathered around him. And they saw some of his disciples eating bread when they had not washed their hands and they found fault. *For all the Judeans and the Pharisees do not eat unless they wash their hands carefully because they keep the tradition of the Elders. And coming from the marketplace, unless they bathe, they do not eat. And there are many other things which they had received to keep: washings of cups and pots and copper vessels and of beds.*"
* Mark 7:1-4

> "And when it was Friday evening, *which is before the Sabbath*,"
* Mark 15:42

> "And Yosip also went up from Galilee from the city, Nazareth, to Judea *to the city of David, which is called Bethlehem*, because he was from the house and from the lineage of David;"
* Luke 2:4

> "And the Samaritan woman said to him, “How is it that you, a Jew, would ask me, a Samaritan woman, for a drink?” *For the Jews do not associate with the Samaritans*."
* John 4:9

> "Now the Passover, *a Jewish festival*, was near."
* John 6:4

Note that all of the texts above are translated from Peshitta, not from Greek. So the Peshitta itself shows explanations of Jewish customs, which doesn’t make sense if, as Aramaic Primacists claim, the New Testament was originally written for Aramaic-speaking Jews.

### Why does the book of Acts show Greek-speaking Christians in Jerusalem?

Even the Peshitta, in Acts 6:1,5, shows that there were Hellenists (Greek-speaking Jews), in Jerusalem who were members of the Christian community at the very beginning of the Christian Era. This directly contradicts the Aramaic Primacy claim that the earliest Christians were all Aramaic-speaking Jews. And if they weren’t all Aramaic speakers, then why should we assume that the writers didn’t know Greek? And therefore, why should we assume that the original NT text couldn’t have been Greek?

In verse 5, the seven deacons chosen to administer alms equally to the Hebrew-speaking and Greek-speaking believers all had Greek names. In Acts 9:29 the deacon Stephen was debating with Greek-speaking Jews about the divinity of Christ. Aramaic primacists claim that Palestine was exclusively Aramaic speaking, so where did these Greek-Speaking Jews in Jerusalem come from? And how did Stephen debate with them if he didn’t know Greek?

### Why is Luke, the author of the Gospel of Luke and the Acts of the Apostles, described as not being a Jew? And if he wasn’t a Jew, how could he have written Luke and Acts in Aramaic?

Colossians 4:10-14 mentions three individuals (Aristarchus, Mark and Jesus/Justus) who send their greetings, and are mentioned in verse 11 as being the only ones working with Paul who are “of the circumcision,” or as some translations put it, “Jews.” Following this, there are three other individuals mentioned as also working with Paul and also sending their greetings – one of these three who are not “of the circumcision” is none other than “Luke, the doctor,” the author of the Gospel of Luke and the Acts of the Apostles. So Luke, not a Jew, could not have been expected to have been fluent in Aramaic, nor have written his two books (which together account for about 27.5% of the New Testament text, the most of any single NT author) in Aramaic. Even the name Luke is of Latin origin, not Semitic.

It is also worth noting that in both books attributed to him, he makes frequent “allusions and references to, and quotations of, ancient Classical and Hellenistic Greek authors, such as Homer, Aesop, Epimenides, Euripides, Plato, and Aratus” indicating “that he was familiar with actual Greek literary texts,” and that he most likely had a classical Hellenistic education, making him intimately familiar with the Greek language, whether or not it was his first language.[^1]

### Why did all of the visiting Jews on Pentacost not understand Aramaic and require the gift of speaking in tongues in order to understand the disciples’ preaching?

The story I’m referring to occurred in Acts 2:4-11. Here is this passage from Bauscher’s Aramaic NT translation (emphasis added):

> **<sup>4</sup>** “And all of them were filled with The Spirit of Holiness, and they were going out speaking in various languages, according to whatever The Spirit was giving them to speak. **<sup>5</sup>** But there were men dwelling in Jerusalem who were worshipers of God, Jews from every nation under Heaven. **<sup>6</sup>** And when that noise occurred, the entire populace gathered and was agitated, because each of them heard that they were speaking in their ***dialects***. **<sup>7</sup>** And they were all marveling and were amazed as they were saying, each to the other, “Are not all these who are speaking Galileans? **<sup>8</sup>** How are we hearing, everyone, his own ***dialect*** in which we were born? **<sup>9</sup>** Parthians and Medes and Elamites, and those who dwell in Bayth-Nahrayn, Judeans and Qapodoqians and those who are from the regions of Pontus and of Asia, **<sup>10</sup>** and from the regions of Phrygia and of Pamphylia and of Egypt and of the countries of Libya which are near to Cyrene and those who came from Rome, Jews and proselytes, **<sup>11</sup>** and who are from Crete, and Arabians, behold, we are hearing from those who are speaking in our own ***dialects***, the wonders of God.”

What a bizarre translation: *leshana* as “dialect”. It means “language” everywhere else in the NT (e.g. \- Acts 1:19). But suddenly it means “dialect” here? The reason for this word choice is due to the Aramaic Primacy idea that the earliest converts were all Aramaic speakers, so, according to Aramaic Primacists, this passage would have to mean that the visiting Jews were speaking various local dialects of Aramaic (in spite of the fact that there is, literally, ZERO evidence for local Aramaic dialects in most of the areas mentioned). However, let’s set aside this ahistorical claim for a moment...

Let’s just suppose, for a moment, that it really was different Aramaic dialects being mentioned here. In that case, that would mean that the Aramaic speakers in those different areas wouldn’t understand each other, and they couldn’t understand Palestinian Aramaic either, otherwise, what was the need for the gift of tongues? And if this were the case, then a New Testament written in 1CPA would be USELESS in spreading the Gospel, because none of the different Aramaic-speaking communities would be able to understand it since they all speak different mutually unintelligible dialects\! Therefore, what would be the point of having the NT written originally in Aramaic?

### Why were Christians called Christians?

The word “Christian” occurs 3 times in the New Testament: Acts 11:26, Acts 26:28 and 1 Peter 4:16. In all three cases, the Syriac text uses the Greek-derived term *keristiyana*, not the Syriac equivalent term *messiyana*. If all of the early Christians were Aramaic speakers, then why did the Antiochians name them “christians” and not “messians”?

### How do you explain the Theodoton Inscription?

The Theodoton Inscription is a dedicatory stone that was at the entrance to a first Century synagogue in Jerusalem. The stone is written in Greek.[^2]

### How do you explain a First-Century Synagogue in Capernaum with Greek inscriptions?

[http://www.mfa.gov.il/mfa/israelexperience/history/pages/capernaum%20-%20city%20of%20jesus%20and%20its%20jewish%20synagogue.aspx](http://www.mfa.gov.il/mfa/israelexperience/history/pages/capernaum%20-%20city%20of%20jesus%20and%20its%20jewish%20synagogue.aspx)

All of the inscriptions at this synagogue are in Hebrew or Greek. None are in Aramaic.

### Why are the warnings against entering the temple area in Greek?

> “... upon it stood pillars, at equal distances from one another, declaring the law of purity, some in Greek, and some in Roman letters, that ‘no foreigner should go within that sanctuary’” Josephus BJ 5.5.2[^3]

> “There are actually two extant copies of the warning notices — a partial one here in Jerusalem at the Israel Museum, and a second, complete, in the Istanbul Archaeology Museum — and they are among a small handful of artifacts conclusively belonging to the shrine built by Herod toward the end of the first century CE. Contemporary accounts mentioned their existence, and 1,800 years after the Temple’s destruction, a French archaeologist found a complete copy that had been incorporated into the wall of a Muslim school in Jerusalem’s Old City.”[^4]

If everyone spoke only Aramaic then why is the inscription only in Greek and Latin?

### How do you explain the fact that most contemporary Jewish funerary inscriptions are in Greek?

> "One of the most surprising facts about these funerary inscriptions is that most of them are ***in Greek*** \-- approximately 70 percent; about 12 percent are in Latin; and only 18 percent are in Hebrew or Aramaic.

> "These figures are even more instructive if we break them down between Palestine and the Diaspora. Naturally in Palestine we would expect more Hebrew and Aramaic and less Greek. This is true, but not to any great extent. Even in Palestine approximately **two-thirds** of these inscriptions are in **Greek**.

> "**Apparently for a great part of the Jewish population the daily language was Greek, even in Palestine.** This is impressive testimony to the impact of Hellenistic culture on Jews in their mother country, to say nothing of the Diaspora.

> "In Jerusalem itself about **40 percent** of the Jewish inscriptions from the first century period (before 70 C.E.) are in Greek. We may assume that most Jewish Jerusalemites who saw the inscriptions *in situ* were able to read them"[^5] (emphasis added)

In Jerusalem, the number of Greek epitaphs (40 percent) is proportionate to the number of epitaphs in **all** Semitic languages, including Hebrew and Aramaic.[^6]

In a first-century C.E. tomb near Jericho, a Jewish family nicknamed the Goliaths (because of their extraordinary stature) inscribed **more than half** their epitaphs in **Greek**.[^7] (emphasis added)

> “Of the 534 items which I think may legitimately be counted as Jewish inscriptions of Rome, **405 (76%) are Greek**; of the rest, 123 (23%) are Latin, three are Hebrew, one Aramaic, one bilingual Greek and Latin, one bilingual Aramaic and Greek. From these figures it is quite apparent that the Roman-Jewish community, which existed from about 100 B.C., was Greek-speaking.”[^8] (emphasis added)

> “With reference to funerary and stone inscriptions, Beth She’arim \[located in Southern Galilee\] is considered as the most important cemetery of ancient Palestine from the period ca. 100 BCE—351 CE, since it produced a corpus of Jewish inscriptions that is larger than from any other single site, of which **80 percent** of the inscriptions are in Greek.”[^9] (emphasis added)

Here is a copy of page 447 from *Corpus Inscriptionum Iudaeae/Palaestinae, Volume 1, Jerusalem up to the Destruction of the Temple* showing an example ossuary for an individual named *Iesous* (or Jesus as we would say today) who was buried in Jerusalem sometime during the period of First Century BC to First Century AD.

### How do you explain Philo of Alexandria?

Philo of Alexandria was a first-century Jewish writer who wrote entirely in Greek. He was very well connected politically in Judea and was highly regarded by the population.[^10]

### Why do most Jews of the Western Diaspora write mostly in Greek?

In the west—namely, the Greek-speaking Mediterranean world—the Jews wrote and spoke only Greek, whereas in the east (Palestine and eastward), Hebrew and Aramaic prevailed—although even there were some communities that wrote and spoke Greek.[^11]

The Greek writings of diaspora Jews are not filled with semitic ‘interference’, as we might expect if these authors’ first language was Aramaic or Hebrew, but that the authors of these works usually wrote Greek as if it were their native language.[^12]

But the area in which Jewish life was most completely carried on in Greek was Egypt, and within Egypt Alexandria in particular. As against the numerous references to Jews in voluminous correspondence in Greek, only negligible amounts of written material in Hebrew or Aramaic have survived, out of a period of several centuries.[^13]

### When a Jewish community from Rhodes paid for a dedication stone in the Temple, why did they have it inscribed in Greek?

A dedication stone from the wall of Herod’s Temple was found. The stone testifies about a donation from the Jewish community in Rhodes to help with temple construction costs. The stone is written in Greek which indicates that the Jews of Rhodes spoke Greek, and also implies that the Jews of Jerusalem could read the dedication inscription. Otherwise, why brag about donating money if nobody could read what you had done?[^14]

## *Section 2* : If Peshitta were the original text of the New Testament...

### Why is it written using 4th to 8th Century Edessan Syriac instead of 1st Century Palestinian Aramaic?

In Peshitta all verbs in the 3rd person Masculine Imperfective form use the **n’-** prefix. The only Aramaic dialect that used **that prefix** for **that verb form** was spoken in the 4th to 8th centuries in the area around Edessa and is referred to as Classical Syriac[^15]. All other Aramaic dialects, including First Century Syriac (aka Old Syriac) as well as the dialects of Aramaic spoken in 1st Century Palestine used the **y’-** prefix for the same verb form[^16]. The fact that Peshitta uses the **n’-** prefix for this verb form is linguistic proof that Peshitta was written sometime during the 4th to 8th centuries in or around Edessa.

### Why does Peshitta use ‘geyr’ and ‘deyn’, markers which identify it as a translation from Greek, but also in a manner which is grammatically correct for Greek, but not for Aramaic?

The particles “geyr” (ܓܝܪ) and “deyn” (ܕܝܢ) occur quite a number of times in Peshitta[^17]. The problem is that these words are not Aramaic at all, but rather borrowed from Greek. They only appear in post-4th Century Syriac Christian literature that has been translated from Greek. They are transliterations of the corresponding Greek words “gar” (γὰρ) and “de” (δὲ). In correct Greek grammatical usage, these two particles generally occur as the second word of a phrase. In Aramaic, such particles would always be the first word in a sentence or phrase, never second. But Peshitta not only uses these Greek words, it also imitates the Greek grammatical usage and appear as the second word of a phrase, **in contradiction to correct Aramaic usage**. Thus, their presence and manner of usage is direct linguistic evidence that Peshitta is a translation from a Greek original[^18].

### Why are there so many competing Aramaic New Testaments?

To date, seven different Aramaic text traditions have been discovered. We have the Diatessaron, the Curetonian Gospels, the Sinaitic Syriac, the Peshitta, the Philoxenian, the Harklean and the Palestinian Syriac texts. All of them are different. Very different. If the New Testament were originally composed in Aramaic, then why are there so many different extreme variations? Such variation does not exist in the Greek texts, even when comparing text types. Aramaic primacists would have you believe that there is uniformity among the different manuscripts, but they are are either grossly ignorant, or willfully lying. There is uniformity within Peshitta, but only because there are so few manuscripts available. But comparing these different texts, there are vast differences between them which does not make sense if the original text of the New Testament were in Aramaic.

In addition to the above, some of the Aramaic New Testament texts (such as Heraklean) have documented histories which prove them to be Greek translations.

### Why do the Syriac-speaking early church fathers quote from other Syriac (non-Peshitta) documents prior to the 5th Century?

In the same vein as the previous objection, you find that prior to the 5th Century, all church fathers who wrote in Syriac quoted from non-Peshitta versions. An example is Ephrem the Syrian who quoted exclusively from the Diatessaron. Why doesn’t anyone quote from Peshitta prior to the 5th Century if it was the original? Wouldn’t the early writers have had a high reverence for the original text? And wouldn’t they be consistent in all quoting from the same original? But their Aramaic quotes come from a variety of sources, including some that are not even listed in the above question. And not one of them claims Aramaic as the original text of the New Testament.

### Why don’t any early church fathers claim Aramaic as the original text of the New Testament?

And to the previous point, why don’t any of the Syriac church fathers claim Aramaic as the original language, especially when some of them were known to have translated some of the previously mentioned NT texts from Greek?

### Why weren’t 5 books of the New Testament included in Peshitta until later?

It is known that no early manuscripts of Peshitta included 2 Peter, 2 John, 3 John, Jude or Revelation. These were not included in the Peshitta Syriac canon until Athanasios I, head of the Syriac church in the East (at the insistence of the church in the west) requested Thomas of Harqel and Paul of Tella to retranslate the entire New Testament from Greek into Syriac, the new translation to include the above-mentioned five omitted books. While the new translation is referred to as Harclensis (or Harklean), the five books were copied from Harclensis for inclusion in Peshitta, such that it is a known, documented fact that these five books were absolutely translated from Greek.[^19]
